'''Smoky Dawson''', [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE (C)]], [[Order of Australia|AM]] (19 March 1913{{spaced ndash}}13 February 2008), born '''Herbert Henry Brown''' and known as '''Herbert Henry Dawson''', was an Australian [[country music]] performer. He was widely touted as Australia's first singing [[Cowboy#Popular culture|cowboy]]: [[Powerhouse Museum]] described him as "a singer, showman, songwriter, scriptwriter, knife and double-headed axe thrower and all round performer who has lived a long life entertaining audiences. Through his radio serials, comic books and songs he created the persona of a happy-go-lucky singing cowboy". In 1985 he published his [[autobiography]], ''Smoky Dawson: A Life''. For his service to country music Dawson was awarded an Order of the British Empire <U+2013> Member (Civil) (December 1982), a Member of the Order of Australia (January 1999) and was inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]] in 2005. Dawson died on 13 February 2008 after a short illness, aged 94. His wife of over 60 years, Florence "Dot" Dawson (n<U+00E9>e Cheers), died on 27 October 2010 at 104 years.

==Biography==
Smoky Dawson was born as Herbert Henry Brown on 19 March 1913 in [[Collingwood, Victoria|Collingwood]].<ref name="Edwardian Index">{{cite AV media |people= |year=1997 |title= Edwardian Index, Victoria 1902-1913 |trans_title= |medium= |language= |url= |accessdate= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format=[[CD-ROM]] |time= |publisher=[[Government of Victoria (Australia)|The Crown in the State of Victoria]]: Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages |location= |id= |isbn=978-0-73110-614-1 |oclc= |quote=|ref= }}
* Henry Herbert Brown born 1913, Collingwood, Registration No.&nbsp;2726
* Parker Frederick Brown married Olive Amy Muir, 1905, Registration No.&nbsp;6942
* Leslie Muir Woods born 1904, Northcote, Registration No.&nbsp;12496
* Laura Olive Emily Brown born 1906, Melbourne West, Registration No.&nbsp;20568
* Peter Frederick James Brown born 1908, Coburg, Registration No.&nbsp;2311 </ref><ref name="HHBrownWW2">{{cite web | url = http://www.ww2roll.gov.au/Veteran.aspx?serviceId=A&veteranId=527887 | title = Service Record: Brown, Herbert Henry | work = World War Two Nominal Roll | publisher = [[Commonwealth of Australia]] | accessdate = 1 January 2013 }}</ref><!-- Smoky's birth name is often given incorrectly as Herbert Henry Dawson. --> His father, Parker Frederick Peter Brown (21 November 1884 <U+2013> 1957), was a [[laborer|labourer]] of [[Irish people|Irish descent]];<ref name="Pioneer Index">{{cite AV media |people= |year=1998 |title= Pioneer Index, Victoria 1836-1888 |trans_title= |medium= |language= |url= |accessdate= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format=[[CD-ROM]] |time= |publisher=[[Government of Victoria (Australia)|The Crown in the State of Victoria]]: Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages |location= |id= |isbn=0-73115-300-6  |oclc= |quote=|ref= }}
* Parker Frederick Peter Brown born 1885, Footscray, Registration No.&nbsp;2709 </ref><ref name="ServiceParker">{{cite web | url = http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/scripts/Imagine.asp?B=1800644 | title = Digital Copy of Item with Barcode 1800644 | publisher = [[National Archives of Australia]] | date = 21 August 2006 | accessdate = 1 January 2013 }}</ref><ref name="Death Index">{{cite AV media |people= |year=1998 |title= Death Index, Victoria 1921-1985 |trans_title= |medium= |language= |url= |accessdate= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format=[[CD-ROM]] |time= |publisher=[[Government of Victoria (Australia)|The Crown in the State of Victoria]]: Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages |location= |id= |isbn= 0-73115-302-2 |oclc= |quote=|ref= }}
* Parker Brown died 1957, aged 72, Heidelberg, Registration No.&nbsp;12431
* Laura Olive Emily Maxwell n<U+00E9>e Brown died 1941, aged 33, Mont Park, Registration No.&nbsp;2231
* Peter Frederick Brown died 1972, aged 64, Box Hill, Registration No.&nbsp;8913
* Edward Parker Dawson died 1978, aged 63, Parkville, Registration No.&nbsp;6199 </ref> his mother, Olive "Amy" Muir (ca. 1880<U+2013>June 1919), was of [[Scottish people|Scottish descent]].<ref name="Bio2">{{cite web | url = http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/dawson/interview2.html | title = Full Interview <U+2013> Smoky Dawson <U+2013> Interview Transcript Tape 2 | last = Hughes | first = Robin | publisher = Australian Biography Project ([[Screen Australia]], [[Commonwealth of Australia]]) | date = 7 February 1994 | accessdate = 28 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name="Great War Index">{{cite AV media |people= |year=1997 |title= Great War Index, Victoria 1914-1920 |trans_title= |medium= |language= |url= |accessdate= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |format=[[CD-ROM]] |time= |publisher=[[Government of Victoria (Australia)|The Crown in the State of Victoria]]: Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages |location= |id= |isbn= 0-73110-616-4  |oclc= |quote=|ref= }}
* Olive Amy Brown died 1919, aged 39, Richmond, Registration No.&nbsp;18833
* Leslie Muir Wood Brown died 1920, aged 17, Kangaroo Ground, Registration No.&nbsp;14930
* Edward Parker Peter Brown born 1915, Brunswick North, Registration No.&nbsp;1215 </ref> His parents married in 1905,<ref name="Edwardian Index"/> and they had five children, Leslie Muir Wood "Les" (1904<U+2013>1920),<ref name="Edwardian Index"/><ref name="Great War Index"/><ref name="Drowned"/> Laura Olive Emily (1906<U+2013>1941),<ref name="Edwardian Index"/><ref name="Death Index"/> Peter Frederick James (1908<U+2013>1972),<ref name="Edwardian Index"/><ref name="Death Index"/> Herbert Henry "Herbie", and Edward Parker Peter "Ted" (aka Ted Dawson) (1915<U+2013>1978).<ref name="Edwardian Index"/><ref name="Great War Index"/><ref name="Bio1">{{cite web | url = http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/dawson/intertext1.html | title = Full Interview <U+2013> Smoky Dawson <U+2013> Interview Transcript Tape 1 | last = Hughes | first = Robin | publisher = Australian Biography Project ([[Screen Australia]], [[Commonwealth of Australia]]) | date = 7 February 1994 | accessdate = 28 December 2012 }}</ref> The Browns initially lived in Melbourne and briefly moved to the rural area of [[Warrnambool, Victoria|Warrnambool]].<ref name="AMGBio">{{cite web | url = {{Allmusic | pure_url=yes | class=artist | id=p647049 }} | title=Smoky Dawson | publisher = [[Rovi Corporation]] | work = [[Allmusic]] | accessdate = 29 December 2012 }}</ref> His father, Parker Brown, also worked as in a [[pharmacist|dispensary]],<ref name="ServiceParker"/><ref name="Service1885">{{cite web | url = http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/scripts/Imagine.asp?B=1800644 | title = Brown Parker : SERN 1885 : POB Yarravill Vic : POE Melbourne Vic : NOK W Brown A | publisher = [[National Archives of Australia]] | date = 21 August 2006 | accessdate = 1 January 2013 }}</ref> and had performed as a baritone under the name, Frederick Parker, at the Bijou in Melbourne.<ref name="Bio1"/> Parker had studied as a medical student before serving in [[World War 1]].<ref name="ServiceParker"/><ref name="AMGBio"/> He enlisted in the Australian Army in June 1915 and fought at [[Gallipoli]] from October until January 1916.<ref name="ServiceParker"/> He was diagnosed with [[neurasthenia]] and was discharged in August 1916 on medical grounds.<ref name="ServiceParker"/> Dawson later remembered, "[m]y dad went to Gallipoli ... but unfortunately he suffered a lot from it and so did the family".<ref name="Hughes">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/tasmania/stories/s871043.htm | title = Smokey Dawson: Country Music Legend | last = Hughes | first = Peter | work = Backyard Stories | publisher = ABC Tasmania. [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) | date = 3 June 2003 | accessdate = 28 December 2012 }}</ref> In June 1919 his mother, Amy, died of unspecified causes and the following year his brother, Les, died by drowning on Christmas Day.<ref name="Drowned">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4563393 | title = Family Notices | newspaper = [[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1956)]] | date = 30 December 1920 | accessdate = 1 January 2012 | page = 1 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref><ref name="Bio1"/><ref name="Jinman"/> By that time his father had remarried.<ref name="Drowned"/>

Parker was prone to heavy drinking and violence, Dawson repeatedly ran away from home after his beatings.<ref name="Bio2"/><ref name="Bio1"/> Once he was nearly choked to death, ran off and, after being caught, he was chained in a dog's cage by his father.<ref name="Jinman">{{cite news | url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/the-adventures-of-smoky-dawson/2008/02/14/1202760487665.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 | title = The Adventures of Smoky Dawson | last = Jinman | first = Richard | newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 15 February 2008 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 }}</ref> From the age of eight or nine he was "making up little ditties" which soothed him.<ref name="Phillips"/> At about nine-years-old, Dawson was so severely beaten that he ran away from home again.<ref name="Bio2"/><ref name="Bio1"/> He travelled to his mother's family, the Muirs, in Melbourne and was sent, by a court order, to live for three years at St. Vincent de Paul's Boys' Orphanage, South Melbourne.<ref name="Bio2"/><ref name="Bio1"/> It was administered by the Catholic Church's [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]], Dawson was baptised in that faith and took a [[Confirmation#Confirmation name|confirmation name]], Aidan.<ref name="Bio2"/> For school holidays he was sent to a farm near [[Birregurra, Victoria|Birregurra]] run by the Carews.<ref name="Bio2"/> He had learned to sing at the orphanage and Jack Carew taught him to play the harmonica and piano accordion.<ref name="Bio2"/> At the age of thirteen Dawson left the orphanage to join his older brother, Peter, working on a farm at Stewarton (about {{convert|8|mi|km}} from [[Goorambat, Victoria|Goorambat]]).<ref name="Bio3">{{cite web | url = http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/dawson/interview3.html | title = Full Interview <U+2013> Smoky Dawson <U+2013> Interview Transcript Tape 3 | last = Hughes | first = Robin | publisher = Australian Biography Project ([[Screen Australia]], [[Commonwealth of Australia]]) | date = 7 February 1994 | accessdate = 28 December 2012 }}</ref> Each Saturday night he would sing at the local town hall with a repertoire that included "[[Funicul<U+00EC>, Funicul<U+00E0>|Finiculi, Finicula]]", "Little Brown Cottage" and "Good Morning, Good Morning".<ref name="Bio3"/>

==Music career==
In 1932 Smoky Dawson worked at a tannery and on weekends he played a [[lap steel guitar]] in a duo, The Coral Island Boys, with his younger brother, Ted, on [[Classical guitar|Spanish guitar]].<ref name="TimeOut">{{cite news | url = http://www.au.timeout.com/sydney/the-bridge/features/742/smoky-dawson | title = Smoky Dawson | work = [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Sydney]] | publisher = [[Time Out (company)|Time Out]] | date = 13 April 2010 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 }}</ref> Both sang lead vocals, with Ted's singing described by Dawson as "a much richer voice than mine. He had more depth in his voice".<ref name="Bio3"/> They performed then-popular songs, such as "Gee But I'm Lonesome for You Caroline" and "Southern Moon Keep on Shining".<ref name="Bio3"/> In 1934 Dawson formed a [[Western music (North America)|Western group]] with an accordionist, a bass guitarist, and Malcolm<!-- last name not given in following ref --> on violin; which cut a [[Acetate disc|test acetate]] at Fidelity Records with Jack Murray recording.<ref name="Bio3"/> It was the first professional use of Dawson's nickname, "Smoky" <U+2013> he had tried pipe smoking when living at Stewarton but it had sickened him.<ref name="Bio3"/><ref name="Adelaide1949"/> The recording led to sponsorship by [[Pepsodent]] <U+2013> a toothpaste company <U+2013> and so the group were named, Smoky and the Pepsodent Rangers.<ref name="ACMF">{{cite web | url = http://www.countrymusichalloffame.com.au/RollOfRenown/1978_SmokyDawson.htm | title = Australian Country Music Roll of Renown <U+2013> Smoky Dawson MBE(C), AM 1978 | publisher = Australian Country Music Hall of Fame. [[Country Music Association of Australia]] | accessdate = 29 December 2012 }}</ref> In 1935 they were the first Western group to be broadcast live on an Australian radio station, [[Gold 104.3|3KZ]], and by 1937 Dawson had his own radio show.<ref name="Bio3"/><ref name="ACMF"/> His show was re-broadcast into New South Wales on [[2CH]] as "Hill-billy Artists" by "Smoky" Dawson and His Boys.<ref name="SMH1937">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17417124 | title = Broadcasting | newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald|The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 <U+2013> 1954)]] | date = 14 September 1937 | accessdate = 29 December 2012 | page = 3 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> In 1941 he signed with [[Columbia Records]], where he recorded his first commercial releases, including "I'm a Happy Go Lucky Cowhand" and "The Range in the Western Sky".<ref name="AMGBio"/> He also toured around Australia.<ref name="Melb Obs">{{cite news | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20050521180014/http://www.melbourneobserver.com.au/ob050309.pdf | title = 80 Years of the Greater 3UZ | work = [[Melbourne Observer]] | publisher = Local Media Pty (Ash Long) | date = 9 Mar 2005 | page = 11 | format = [[PDF]] | accessdate = 29 December 2012 }}</ref>

Dawson had used music as a way of comforting himself and during [[World War II]] he took this talent to boost the morale of others.<ref name="Moremon">{{cite web | url = http://ajrp.awm.gov.au/ajrp/remember.nsf/pages/NT000021CA | title = Smokey Dawson: First Australian Army Entertainment Unit (People) | last = Moremon | first = John | publisher = Australia Japan Research Project. [[Australian War Memorial]] | date = 1 June 2004 | accessdate = 28 December 2012 }}</ref> In 1939 upon the outbreak of the war he had attempted to enlist, but was rejected on medical grounds for a "bumpy heart".<ref name="Moremon"/> In 1940, with Smoky Dawson's Five-Star Rangers, he would perform at soldier's socials.<ref name="Argus1940">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12433255 |title=Soldiers' Social | newspaper=[[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 <U+2013> 1956)]] | date = 13 March 1940 | accessdate = 29 December 2012 | page = 20 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> In 1941 when the Japanese forces approached Australia, he enlisted as a non-combatant nursing orderly and was commandeered by the First Australian Army Entertainment Unit.<ref name="Moremon"/> On 13 March 1944, while still in the army, he married Florence "Dot" Cheers (12 October 1906{{spaced ndash}}27 October 2010),<ref name="O'Neill"/><ref name="Radio Info Dot">{{cite web | url = http://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/5786 | title = Happy 100th Birthday Dot Dawson | publisher = Radio Info | date = 12 October 2006 | accessdate = 3 January 2013 }}</ref> an elocution teacher <U+2013> they had met nine years earlier when both worked in radio.<ref name="Phillips"/><ref name="ACMF"/> ''[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]]''{{'}}s Louis Clark, described Dawson as an "Australian outback songster" and the unit as "an array of genius".<ref name="Clark">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38562383 | title = The War's Greatest Morale Builders | last = Clark | first = Louis | newspaper = [[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail (Perth, WA : 1885 <U+2013> 1954)]] | date = 29 November 1945 | page = 60 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] | accessdate = 30 December 2012 }}</ref> Aside from music, Dawson would also perform at rodeos, circuses and country shows demonstrating his skill at knife-throwing using machetes, cammando knives, tomahawks, or two-edged axes.<ref name="Adelaide1949"/><ref name="AxeThrow">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79821377 |title=Cameraman Braves Axe |newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News (Perth, WA : 1882 <U+2013> 1950)]] |date=22 March 1949 |accessdate=31 December 2012 |page=15 Edition: Home |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> By October 1949, Dawson had recorded about 60 tracks from his songbook of 280 tunes <U+2013> all of them "have a cowboy setting<U+2014>with a dash of romance".<ref name="Adelaide1949">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article55780581 | title = Smoky learnt all the old folk lore | newspaper = [[Sunday Mail (Adelaide)|The Mail (Adelaide, SA : 1912 <U+2013> 1954)]] | date = 8 October 1949 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 | page = 24 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> Dawson travelled around Australia for eight months a year while Dot remained behind as Auntie June on her own radio show for 3KZ.<ref name="Adelaide1949"/>

In March 1951 Dawson, as a cowboy entertainer, narrated a documentary film, directed by [[Rudall Hayward]], on Australian rough riders at a [[Kyabram]] rodeo, which was to be broadcast on United States TV.<ref name="Rough">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23036480 | title = They're rough, tough men in fancy shirts <U+2013> They're on 'T.V.' | newspaper = [[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 <U+2013> 1956)]] | date = 13 March 1951 | accessdate = 30 December 2012 | page = 20 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> Dawson sang a self-written song praising their skills and noted "there's nothing half-baked about Australian rodeos or the boys who ride in them. They're entitled to all the credit we can give them ... Rodeos and rough riders are just as much a part of our national heritage as symphonies and seascapes".<ref name="Rough"/> In June that year Dawson and Dot travelled to the US where he recorded and played at the [[Grand Ole Opry]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]]. While in [[New Jersey]], he took the role of [[Petruchio]] in a stage version of the musical, ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]''.<ref name="KissMe">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23210876 | title = 'Smoky's' Back from USA | newspaper = [[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 <U+2013> 1956)]] | date = 4 October 1952 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 | page = 12 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> When Dawson returned to Australia in September 1952 he was hailed as an "Australian singing 'cowboy' who has made good in the US at the expense of the world's best".<ref name="Cowboy">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47415955 | title = Children Greet Cowboy Singer | newspaper = [[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 <U+2013> 1954)]] | date = 29 September 1952 | accessdate = 30 December 2012 | page = 6 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> For trick riding his [[palomino]] horse, Flash (1951<U+2013>1982), was bedecked in American-style tack rather than Australian.<ref name="Phillips">{{cite web | url = http://www.nla.gov.au/ntwkpubs/gw/46/p20a01.html | archiveurl = http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/11779/20040524-0000/www.nla.gov.au/ntwkpubs/gw/46/p20a01.html | title = Where there's 'Smoky' there's life and laughter | last = Phillips | first = Nancy | work = Gateways | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] | date = August 2000 | archivedate = 24 May 2004 | issue = 46 | issn = 1039-3498 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name="Flash">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71700990 | title = The horse that wouldn't go home | newspaper = [[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1956)]] | date = 13 October 1955 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 | page = 1 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> Flash lived to be 31 years old and Dawson supplemented his feed by giving him porridge with a spoon. Echoing US singing cowboy, [[Roy Rogers]], on 8 December 1952 Dawson starred in his own radio show, ''The Adventures of Smoky Dawson'', which stayed on the air for ten years until 1962.<ref name="Phillips"/><ref name="ShowStart">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47515388 | title = Smoky Dawson on 5 AD Tonight | newspaper = [[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 - 1954)]] | date = 8 December 1952 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 | page = 4 | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref>

At its peak, Dawson's show was broadcast on 69 stations across the country. Dot also had her own radio shows for children. A related comic book of the same name was published from 1953 to 1962 and both featured "Dawson's persona [which] became 'Australia's favourite cowboy', with his faithful sidekick Jingles, his horse Flash and their young friend Billy fighting the evil outlaw Grogan, adhering to Smoky's 'code of the west', pausing for a song, a moral and sometimes a bowl of cornflakes, courtesy of the program's sponsor".<ref name="PHMuse">{{cite web |url=http://from.ph/346889 |title=2004/168/4 Comic book, ''The Adventures of Smoky Dawson No 10'', paper / ink, published by KG Murray Publishing Co, printed by Sungravure Ltd, Rosebery, New South Wales, Australia, 1953-1962 |author=Powerhouse Museum |accessdate=31 December 2012 |publisher=[[Powerhouse Museum|Powerhouse Museum, Australia]] }}</ref> For the radio show Dawson provided "rendition[s] of a magpie, kookaburra, rooster, turkey, pig, cow, an impatient horse, a posse with bloodhounds (with the bandit being shot), a pack of dogs fighting and next door's dog howling in the middle of the night".<ref name="Phillips"/> In 1957 he founded the Smoky Dawson Ranch on a {{convert|26|acre|ha}} farm at [[Ingleside, New South Wales|Ingleside]] as a venue to host country music shows, a horse riding school and a holiday camp for children.<ref name="AMGBio"/><ref name="Jinman"/><ref name="TimeOut"/>

In 1974 a TV series, ''Luke's Kingdom'', was shot at Dawson's ranch.<ref name="TimelineBio">{{cite news | url = http://www.capitalnews.com.au/editorial.asp?editorial_id=1342&issue=100 | title = Smoky Dawson <U+2013> A Most Extraordinary Life | newspaper = Country Music Capital News | publisher = [[Rural Press]], [[John Fairfax Holdings]] | date = March 2008 | volume = 33 | issue = 3 | accessdate = 3 January 2013 }}</ref> The following year he featured on ''[[This Is Your Life (Australian TV series)|This Is Your Life]]'' hosted by [[Mike Willesee]].<ref name="TimelineBio"/> In 1988 he appeared in two episodes of TV soap opera, ''[[A Country Practice]]'', as a drifter, " Charlie McKeahnie", who passes through the fictional location of Wandin Valley and proposes to town gossip, "Esme Watson".<ref name="TimelineBio"/> His performance was so popular with viewers that he made another appearance the following year. Dawson was a [[Freemason]].<ref>[http://www.freemasonrysaust.org.au/freemason.html#famous "What is Freemasonry?"]</ref>

==Awards and legacy==
Smoky Dawson had a long career of recording and performing followed his radio show, and he enjoyed performing until he died. He has frequently been recognised for his contributions to music and entertainment. In 1977, with [[Tex Morton]] and [[Buddy Williams (country musician)|Buddy Williams]], Dawson was inducted into the Hands of Fame at [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]].<ref name="TimelineBio"/> On 31 December 1982 Dawson was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|Order of the British Empire <U+2013> Member (Civil)]] with the citation, "In recognition of service to country music".<ref name="MBEC">{{cite web | url = http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?breif=false&page=1&search_view=~all~&view=10&search_type=advanced | title = Search Results for Awardee: Dawson, Herbert Henry | publisher = It's an Honour <U+2013> [[Government of Australia]] | accessdate = 30 December 2012 }}</ref> In 1983 he was named on the Australian Country Music Roll of Renown. In 1985 he published his [[autobiography]], ''Smoky Dawson: A Life''.<ref name="DawsonBio">{{cite book | first = Dawson | last = Smoky | others = Illustrated by [[Pro Hart]], Introduction by [[R. M. Williams]] | titl e= Smoky Dawson : a life | publication-date = 1985 | publisher = [[Allen & Unwin]] | location = Sydney | isbn = 978-0-86861-774-9 }}</ref> In 1988 Dawson and Trevor Knight won The Heritage Golden Guitar at the [[Country Music Awards of Australia]] for "The Days of Old Khancoban" <U+2013> written by Dawson about the droving days of his youth in the Snowy Mountains. The following year Dawson and Knight won a second Golden Guitar for their song, "High Country", as Best Vocal Duo or Group.

In 1994 [[Film Australia]] broadcast his biography based on taped interviews by Robin Hughes for the Australian Biography Project.<ref name="BioMain">{{cite web | url = http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/dawson/ | title = Smoky Dawson <U+2013> Introduction | last = Hughes | first = Robin | publisher = Australian Biography Project ([[Screen Australia]], [[Commonwealth of Australia]]) | date = 7 February 1994 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 }}</ref> On [[Australia Day]] (26 January) 1999 Dawson was made a [[Order of Australia|Member of the Order of Australia]] with the citation, "In recognition of service to country music".<ref name="MBEC"/> In 2005 he was inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame|Australian Record Industry Association Hall of Fame]]. He has also been recognised in the US, and received the Honor Award of the Grand Ole Opry. In April 2007 he donated his first electric guitar to the [[Australian Stockman's Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite news|first=|last=|coauthors=|title=Smoky Dawson donates guitar to Hall of Fame|date=2007-04-09|publisher=ABC News|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200704/s1892680.htm |work=|pages=|accessdate=2007-04-09|language=}}</ref> Smoky's Bar and Grill was opened in his name in 2005 at the West Diggers Club in Tamworth <U+2013> he attended with Dot. His recording career spanned more than six decades, his last album, ''Homestead of My Dreams'', was released in 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://phobos.apple.com/WebObjects/MZStore.woa/wa/viewAlbum?id=112105127&s=143441 | title = ''Homestead of My Dreams'' }}</ref><ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/folk-legend-smoky-dawson-dies/2008/02/14/1202760445577.html "Folk legend Smoky Dawson dies"]</ref>

[[Powerhouse Museum]] described him as "a singer, showman, songwriter, scriptwriter, knife and double-headed axe thrower and all round performer who has lived a long life entertaining audiences. Through his radio serials, comic books and songs he created the persona of a happy-go-lucky singing cowboy".<ref name="PHMuse"/> From 2001 the museum has displayed his signed copy of the comic book, ''The Adventures of Smoky Dawson'', and other memorabilia, which was subsequently donated by Dawson in 2004.<ref name="PHMuse"/>

==Death==
In his later years Smoky Dawson was diagnosed with arthritis, emphysema and two hernias. In June 2000 he was knocked down by a hit-and-run driver and had spinal injuries.<ref name="PHMuse"/> As of 2004 he and Dot presented a radio show on [[2NSB]] and lived in [[Lane Cove, New South Wales]].
Herbert Henry "Smoky" Dawson died on 13 February 2008 after a short illness, a month short of his 95th birthday.<ref name="O'Neill"/> He was survived by his wife, Florence "Dot" Dawson, who died on 27 October 2010 at 104 years of age.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/breaking-news/smoky-dawsons-wife-dot-passes-away/story-e6frf7kf-1225944818866 "Smoky Dawson's wife Dot passes away"]. [[Herald Sun]], 28 October 2010, Accessed on 28 October 2010</ref> In a 2005 interview Dawson indicated how he would like to be remembered, "Ah well, just as Herb. Just as one who's tried his best, he's carried out, lover of his country and always thought about the good things in life. Being honest and true to yourself, main thing, true to yourself. And ah, I think to be remembered as an old friend".<ref name="O'Neill">{{cite news | url = http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2007/s2163226.htm | title = Smoky Dawson Dies at 94 | last = O'Neill | first = Sharon | work = [[The 7.30 Report]] | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) | date = 14 February 2008 | accessdate = 31 December 2012 }}</ref>

